I would like to use async hooks provided by Node.js to implement request context (having context without manually passing it everywhere). I saw some implementations using middleware to initialise request context:

```
const contextMiddleware = (req, res, next) => {
  // initialize request context
  const cxt = asyncContext.create({ parent: asyncHooks.executionAsyncId() });
  // take Request ID from request headers and store it into context
  cxt.set("request-id", req.get("X-Request-Id"))

  next();
};
```

This code says that async resource executing middleware code is parent of request context. So any code invoked by this async resource is going to share the same request context.

This approach works until you use something like `morgan` to log request which uses `on-finished` under the hood. Where code is executed outside of our request context so metadata such as Request ID aren't available within logs produced by `morgan`.

Is there any other better place to initialise request context other than within middleware to capture entire request lifecycle (including executing of `on-finished`)? Or would be using 

```
const cxt = asyncContext.create({ parent: asyncHooks.triggerAsyncId() });
```

instead within middleware viable solution? Saying that root of request context is parent of resource executing middleware code (isn't parent resource reused among multiple requests? As it would cause leaking of request context among different requests)

I would be glad for any feedback. Thank you!

