By default, Router handles unhandled options requests. This becomes a real headache if you want to handle those requests on top of a router tree.

Let me clarify with an example

```js
const express = require('express');

const rootRouter = express.Router();

// These routers above have many routes inside them.
const myChildRouter = express.Router();
const mySecondChildRouter = express.Router();

// I don't care about what happening in those routers.
rootRouter.all('/myfeaturemodule1', myChildRouter);
rootRouter.all('/myfeaturemodule2', mySecondChildRouter);

// When I route to an indistinct route that does not start with feature module paths my callback will be called.
// However when I route to any indistinct route that starts with feature module paths
// my callback will never fire since child routers will be handling the unhandled options request

rootRouter.use((req,res) => {
    if (! req.route ) {
        // Route is unhandled
        // My logic goes here
    }
})
```

To work around this I need to put my handler to end of every router on the router tree.

my suggestion is adding an option to disable this behavior let the parent route handle that request.

